        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-08-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-08-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="30"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d30">
                <head>30. Circular Message From the United States Information Agency to the Embassy
                    in Thailand<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d30fn1">Source: National Archives,
                            <gloss target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 306, Office of Policy and Plans,
                        1963–1969, General Subject Files, 1949–1970, Entry UD–264, Box 313, Master
                        Copies 1969. Confidential; Immediate. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAG_1">Gabor</persName>; cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJW_1">Shirley</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HWG_1"
                            >Hamilton</persName>, Hitchkok, and <persName corresp="#p_BWF_1"
                            >Bennett</persName> (at 3 p.m.); approved in substance by <persName
                            corresp="#p_WBM_1">White</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_BWF_1"
                            >Bennett</persName> initialed for both Hitchkok and <persName
                            corresp="#p_WBM_1">White</persName>. Repeated to Djkarta, Lahore,
                        London, Manila, New Delhi, and Saigon. Sent via telegram.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <idno type="document-identifier">USIA–12811</idno>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-08-02">August 2, 1969</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following guidance received from Presidential party and given to <gloss
                        target="#t_USIA_1">USIA</gloss> media:</p>
                <p>1. The Nixon administration intends this to be an era of negotiations in which
                    American Foreign Policy will not be based on the assumption of intrinsic
                    hostility, unless such hostility is demonstrated by specific action.</p>
                <p>2. Peace in Asia—which is a precondition to peace in the world—cannot result
                    primarily from American conceptions but has to involve Asian initiatives and
                    regional and sub-regional arrangements that have an Asian origin.</p>
                <p>3. The United States would be prepared to support such regional
                    Arrangements—especially in the economic field—if American assistance were
                    requested and, in the U.S. view required.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_SFJ_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SFJ_1">Shakespeare</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
